import PhilosophyCallout from '../../components/docs/PhilosophyCallout.astro';
---

<DocsLayout title="Emotional brief" description="Who Cleo is for and what we owe them">
  <div class="prose">
    <h1>The emotional brief</h1>
    <hr class="section-accent-rule" />

    <h2>Who arrives</h2>
    <p>
      A licensed physical therapist — often clinic lead or senior staff — who has been in practice
      eight to fifteen years. They chose this work to help people move again. They did not choose
      two hours of documentation after every clinic day.
    </p>
    <p>
      They are cognitively exhausted, not lazy. They have tried other software. They have received
      denial letters after doing everything right. They are skeptical of anything that sounds like
      a startup pitch.
    </p>

    <h2>What they feel when they arrive</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Resigned — another tool will probably be more of the same</li>
      <li>Vigilant — watching for hype, hidden costs, and workflow disruption</li>
      <li>Quietly hopeful — they would not be searching if some part of them did not still believe things could change</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>What we owe them</h2>
    <p>
      Acknowledge the difficulty before offering the solution. Never perform enthusiasm they do not
      have energy to match. Prove competence through calm clarity, not feature density. Respect
      that their attention belongs to patients, not to our interface.
    </p>

    <PhilosophyCallout>
      <p>
        Frame 8 is the north star: home for dinner on a Tuesday. Every screen, token, and word in
        Cleo should move the user toward that moment — or get out of the way.
      </p>
    </PhilosophyCallout>
  </div>
</DocsLayout>
